Anonymous Wed 09 Aug 2023 02:04:28 No.58650774 Report
Quoted By: >>58650844 >>58650890 >>58650916
>>58650668
It's difficult for me to imagine an environment where there's so much liquid ammonia on the surface, oceans of it, that life can evolve there using it as the solvent for its biology, without ammonia in gaseous form being a whopping big fraction of the atmosphere too, unless the pressures are so high and the temperatures are so low that it only appears in trace amounts. And empirically speaking, worlds with ammonia-methane atmospheres--reducing atmospheres--may be vastly more common than worlds with oxygen atmospheres. The gas giants in our solar system all have ammonia-methane atmospheres with only traces of anything else. Almost all cometary ices are principally ammonia and methane, and the models suggest that that's where atmospheres principally come from in the first place. The appearance of life that photosynthesizes and slowly converts the atmosphere from reducing to oxidizing may well be an extremely rare fluke.
